description:
This is a simple dataset for you to get started with. Extend it and add it as a new tab by following these instructions:

### Here in SPARQL visualizer

1) Add some more data to the graph

2) Change the description (The editor supports [Markdown](https://github.com/adam-p/markdown-here/wiki/Markdown-Cheatsheet))

3) Copy the dataset to clipboard

![alt text](./assets/step1.png \

)

### In template JSON-file [(Get it here)](./assets/template.json)
Open the file in your preferred text editor. [Visual Studio Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/) is awesome, but Notepad will do. Then continue with these steps:

4) Change the title of the document and add your name(s)

5) Paste in the JSON object (which you should have at your clipboard from *step 3)*)

6) Change the title of the new tab you just added.

![alt text](./assets/step2.png \

)

### Re-configure SPARQL-visualizer
Instead of using the default file, SPARQL-visualizer should use the JSON-file you just configured. This is done by adding (or changing) the `file` URL parameter in the address bar so it looks like this:

`https://madsholten.github.io/sparql-visualizer?file=<PATH_TO_YOUR_FILE>`

`<PATH_TO_YOUR_FILE>` is the path to the JSON-file, and as it must be publicly available there are a few options. The easy one is to just add it to your private Dropbox and create a shared link to the file. When working in a Dropbox directory this is as easy as right-clicking the file and choosing `Copy Dropbox Link`. This will establish a direct link so changes in the file will be directly reflected in the visualizer when refreshing the browser view.

Alternatively, the content of the JSON-file can be copied to a [Github Gist](https://gist.github.com/). Just provide a file name and create a secret or public gist. SPARQL-visualizer needs the raw file, so in the next window, click the *Raw* button. The URL of the raw page can be used as value for `<PATH_TO_YOUR_FILE>`.
